"Li T., Kwon M., Zhao M., Kug J.-S., Luo J.-J., Yu W.","Global warming shifts Pacific tropical cyclone location",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","21", L21804,"","",,,10.1029/2010GL045124,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78249272349&partnerID=40&md5=6a33bed9ad1fa1f671006eb88c5324dd","International Pacific Research Center, University of Hawaii at Manoa, 1680 East-West Rd., Honolulu, HI 96822, United States; Korea Ocean Research and Development Institute, 1270 Sa-dong Sangnok-gu, Ansan, Gyeonggi 426-744, South Korea; GFDL, NOAA, PO Box 308, Princeton, NJ 08542, United States; Research Institute for Climate Change, JAMSTEC, 3173-25 Showa-machi, Kanazawa-ku, Yokohama, Kanagawa 236-0001, Japan; First Institute of Oceanography, State Oceanic Administration, 6, Road Xian-Xia-Ling, Qingdao, Shandong 266061, China","Li, T., International Pacific Research Center, University of Hawaii at Manoa, 1680 East-West Rd., Honolulu, HI 96822, United States; Kwon, M., International Pacific Research Center, University of Hawaii at Manoa, 1680 East-West Rd., Honolulu, HI 96822, United States, GFDL, NOAA, PO Box 308, Princeton, NJ 08542, United States; Zhao, M., GFDL, NOAA, PO Box 308, Princeton, NJ 08542, United States; Kug, J.-S., Korea Ocean Research and Development Institute, 1270 Sa-dong Sangnok-gu, Ansan, Gyeonggi 426-744, South Korea; Luo, J.-J., Research Institute for Climate Change, JAMSTEC, 3173-25 Showa-machi, Kanazawa-ku, Yokohama, Kanagawa 236-0001, Japan; Yu, W., First Institute of Oceanography, State Oceanic Administration, 6, Road Xian-Xia-Ling, Qingdao, Shandong 266061, China","A global high-resolution (∼40 km) atmospheric general circulation model (ECHAM5 T319) is used to investigate the change of tropical cyclone frequency in the North Pacific under global warming. A time slice method is used in which sea surface temperature fields derived from a lower-resolution coupled model run under the 20C3M (in which historical greenhouse gases in 20th century were prescribed as a radiative forcing) and A1B (in which carbon dioxide concentration was increased 1% each year from 2000 to 2070 and then was kept constant) scenarios are specified as the lower boundary conditions to simulate the current and the future warming climate, respectively. A significant shift is found in the location of tropical cyclones from the western to central Pacific. The shift to more tropical cyclones in the central and less in the western Pacific is not attributable to a change in atmospheric static stability, but to a change in the variance of tropical synoptic-scale perturbations associated with a change in the background vertical wind shear and boundary layer divergence. Copyright 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric boundary layer; Atmospheric movements; Atmospheric temperature; Carbon dioxide; Climate models; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Hurricanes; Storms; 20th century; Atmospheric general circulation models; Atmospheric static stability; Carbon dioxide concentrations; Coupled models; High resolution; Lower boundary conditions; North Pacific; Radiative forcings; Sea surface temperatures; Time slice; Tropical cyclone; Vertical wind shear; Warming climate; Western Pacific; Tropics; carbon dioxide; global warming; oceanic general circulation model; perturbation; sea surface temperature; tropical cyclone; turbulent boundary layer; wind shear; Pacific Ocean; Pacific Ocean (North)",,,,,,"Bengtsson, L., Botzet, M., Esch, M., Will greenhouse gas- induced warming over the next 50 years lead to higher frequency and greater intensity of hurricanes? (1996) Tellus, Ser. A, 48, pp. 57-73. , doi:10.1034/ j.1600-0870.1996.00004.x; Bengtsson, L., Hodges, K.I., Esch, M., Keenlyside, N., Komblush, L., Luo, J.J., Yamagata, T., How many tropical cyclones change in a warmer climate (2007) Tellus, Ser. A, 59, pp. 539-561. , doi:10.1111/j.1600-0870. 2007.00251.x; Bretherton, C.S., McCaa, J.R., Grenier, H., A new parameterization for 